:: FlightPrep [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Preflight: reviewing materials at Alpine"])>>

<div class="scenario-title">Within Limits</div>
<div class="scenario-subtitle">A fuel stop at Alpine, a number in the book, and a man who argues for a living</div>

Sunday afternoon, mid-June, Alpine, Texas. You are on the ramp at Alpine-Casparis Municipal (E38), 4,514 feet above sea level and a comfortable hundred degrees in the shade of the wing. The Saratoga's tanks are full because you just made them that way at the self-serve pump, the credit card reader working on the third try. Your logbook says 640 hours. Your back says most of them were this weekend, on the trails of the Chisos Basin.

In the right seat, currently standing in the only shade on the ramp, is Grant Sokol: your brother-in-law, fifty-two, an appellate lawyer with a win rate that gets written about. Three days of hiking have left him sunburned and cheerful. Tomorrow morning at eight he has a deposition in San Antonio he has been preparing for a month. Home is San Marcos Regional, 273 nautical miles east-northeast, about an hour and fifty in this airplane. It is 4:40 in the afternoon. Official sunset is 8:52.

The field is deserted the way small high-desert fields get on summer Sundays. The city office is dark. The wind sock hangs at a diagonal, thinking about it.

You still have the run-up ahead of you. Review your materials, then go fly the airplane.

<div class="chart-disclaimer">Charts, weather data, and performance figures in this scenario are from the period in which it was written and may no longer be current. Use the materials provided here, not current publications, as the scenario is designed around them.</div>

<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Weather &amp; Daylight</span>" "Preflight-Weather">><<set $readWeather to true>><</link>>
<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Route &amp; Terrain</span>" "Preflight-FlightPlan">><<set $readFlightPlan to true>><</link>>
<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Aircraft &amp; Run-up Limits</span>" "Preflight-Aircraft">><<set $readAircraft to true>><</link>>
<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Field Guide: Alpine &amp; Outs</span>" "Preflight-Field">><<set $readField to true>><</link>>

<<if $readWeather and $readFlightPlan and $readAircraft and $readField>>
<hr>
You've seen what there is to see. The airplane is waiting.

<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">☑ Start Up and Taxi</span>" "Opening">><</link>>
<<elseif $readWeather or $readFlightPlan or $readAircraft or $readField>>
<hr>
<em>There's more on the clipboard if you want it. Nobody is timing you except the sun.</em>

<<link "<span class=\"preflight-btn\">Start Up and Taxi Anyway</span>" "Opening">><</link>>
<</if>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-Weather [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed weather and daylight"])>>
<strong>Weather: not the problem today</strong>

<div class="metar-block">E38 (AWOS-3, 119.025) 142150Z AUTO 19007KT 30SM CLR 38/M01 A3009
KMRF 142150Z AUTO 20010KT 10SM CLR 36/M02 A3008
KFST 142153Z AUTO 17008KT 10SM CLR 39/03 A3007
KOZA 142155Z AUTO 16006KT 10SM CLR 37/06 A3006
KHYI 142153Z 16009KT 10SM SCT045 35/17 A3004</div>

<div class="metar-block">TAF KHYI 142130Z 1422/1524 16010KT P6SM SCT050
  FM150300 15007KT P6SM FEW250
  FM151500 16008KT P6SM SCT040</div>

<strong>Winds aloft (FT, 2200Z issuance)</strong>

<div class="metar-block">          6000    9000    12000
MRF area  1908    2012    2215
JCT area  1710    1812    2014</div>

<strong>Daylight math</strong>

<p>Sunset 8:52 PM local. End of civil twilight 9:19. Wheels-up at 5:15 puts you on the ground at San Marcos around 7:10 with the sun still up the whole way. Every hour of delay slides the last part of the flight closer to the dark, and the last part of the flight is the easy part; it's the first hundred miles, over the emptiest country, that you'd rather not do late.</p>

<p>Density altitude at Alpine right now: about 7,600 feet. The airplane knows it even if the field elevation sign doesn't say so.</p>

<<link "← Back to preflight" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-FlightPlan [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed route and terrain"])>>
<strong>The trip home: E38 to KHYI, 273 nm</strong>

<div class="sectional-container">
<img src="/scenarios/within-limits/images/area_map.jpg" alt="Route overview map, Alpine to San Marcos, showing Fort Stockton, Ozona, Junction, and the high country east of Alpine">
<div class="sectional-label">Route overview: E38 direct KHYI. High, empty country for the first hundred miles, then the land steps down toward the Hill Country.</div>
</div>

<div class="flight-plan">Aircraft:    N429TC  Saratoga II HP (PA-32R-301)
Route:       E38 DCT KHYI (VFR, flight following from ABQ Center)
Cruise:      9,500 east / 158 KTAS / about 16 gph
Time:        1+50 at forecast winds
Fuel:        102 gal usable at engine start (topped at Alpine)
Souls:       2</div>

<strong>The terrain ladder, westbound highs to eastbound lows</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>Segment</th><th>Rough min safe</th><th>What's under you</th></tr>
<tr><td>E38 → Marathon</td><td>8,000</td><td>Altuda Pass, the Glass Mountains shoulder, nothing paved</td></tr>
<tr><td>Marathon → Sanderson</td><td>7,000</td><td>Ranch country, canyons cutting toward the Rio Grande</td></tr>
<tr><td>Sanderson → Ozona</td><td>6,000</td><td>Mesas, wind farms, US 90 wandering somewhere south</td></tr>
<tr><td>Ozona → Junction → KHYI</td><td>4,500</td><td>The land relents; I-10, towns, options</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The shape of this route is worth saying out loud: the highest, emptiest, most option-poor flying is the first forty minutes. If the airplane has something to say, you would rather hear it over Junction than over Altuda Pass. Airports with real runways between here and home: Fort Stockton (51 nm north of the early route), Ozona (on the route, 150 out), Junction (on the route, 200 out). Between Alpine and Ozona, mostly what you have is the memory of airports.</p>

<<link "← Back to the clipboard" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-Aircraft [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed aircraft and run-up limits"])>>
<strong>N429TC: 1999 Saratoga II HP</strong>

<div class="aircraft-card">Powerplant:  Lycoming IO-540-K1G5, 300 hp, fuel injected
Ignition:    Dual Slick magnetos, new-to-you (overhauled at
             annual 14 months / 210 hours ago)
Prop:        Hartzell 3-blade constant speed
Fuel:        102 gal usable, 2 tanks
Avionics:    GNS 430W, KX 155, KAP 150 autopilot, JPI EDM-730
Vno:         149 KIAS   Vne: 191 KIAS
Vso:         60 KIAS    Best glide: 92 KIAS @ 3,200 lb</div>

<strong>The run-up numbers (POH, and what they mean)</strong>

<div class="aircraft-card">Magneto check @ 2,000 RPM:
  Max drop on either mag:        175 RPM
  Max difference between mags:    50 RPM</div>

<p>Two things the numbers don't say. First, the mag check is a redundancy check, not a health certificate: you are proving each system can carry the engine alone, because someday one of them may have to. Second, a drop that <em>clears</em> after aggressive leaning is consistent with a fouled spark plug burning itself clean. It is also consistent with an ignition fault that behaves when it feels like behaving. The run-up can tell you the numbers. It cannot tell you which story you're in.</p>

<p>High-elevation footnote: at 7,600 density altitude, full-rich taxi is a plug-fouling machine. Lean for taxi here or pay for it at the run-up pad. Everybody who flies the mountain West learns this once.</p>

<<link "← Back to the ramp" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Preflight-Field [preflight]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reviewed field guide"])>>
<strong>Alpine-Casparis Municipal (E38), elevation 4,514</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>Item</th><th>Fact</th></tr>
<tr><td>Runways</td><td>1/19, 6,002 x 75, asphalt, fair. 5/23, 5,018 x 60, good.</td></tr>
<tr><td>CTAF/UNICOM</td><td>122.8</td></tr>
<tr><td>AWOS-3</td><td>119.025</td></tr>
<tr><td>Center</td><td>Albuquerque Center 135.875 (Fort Stockton RCAG) for flight following and pop-ups</td></tr>
<tr><td>Attendance</td><td>Weekdays and Saturdays. Unattended Sundays and holidays.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fuel</td><td>100LL self-serve, 24 hours, card reader of moody disposition</td></tr>
<tr><td>Maintenance</td><td>Airframe and powerplant shops on the field, closed today. Nearest open option: Monday morning, here or Fort Stockton.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Instrument</td><td>RNAV (GPS) 19 and 23. ODKAE ONE obstacle departure. Special takeoff minimums apply: the terrain is real.</td></tr>
</table>

<strong>The outs, if you need one later</strong>

<table class="airport-table">
<tr><th>Field</th><th>Where</th><th>What's there</th></tr>
<tr><td>KFST Fort Stockton</td><td>51 nm NE of Alpine, north of the early route</td><td>12/30, 7,508 ft. AWOS. Self-serve. Nobody home Sunday night.</td></tr>
<tr><td>KOZA Ozona</td><td>On route, about 150 out</td><td>16/34, 6,003 ft. Quiet. A courtesy car rumor.</td></tr>
<tr><td>KJCT Junction</td><td>On route, about 200 out</td><td>17/35, 5,004 ft. I-10 next door.</td></tr>
<tr><td>KMRF Marfa</td><td>17 nm west (wrong direction)</td><td>Long runways, glider ops, also Sunday-quiet</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Town: two miles. One motel with vacancies in June, a couple more if you're flexible. A one-lot rental car outfit that answers the phone about half the time on weekends. Sul Ross State University up the hill, a good diner, and a sky at night that explains why the observatory is one county over.</p>

<<link "← Back to the rest of it" "FlightPrep">><</link>>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Opening [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Run-up: right mag drops 240, rough"])>>

The IO-540 lights on the second blade and settles into its big-bore idle, that lazy freight-train sound that made you buy this airplane instead of something sensible. Grant folds himself into the right seat, finds the belt buckle on the first try now, sets his phone to silent, and rests a legal pad against his knee out of what you can only assume is habit.

You lean the mixture for the taxi because the field guide is right and everybody does learn it once. Run-up pad, runway 19, nose into what little wind there is. Flows, checklist, trim, controls. Prop cycle: clean. Then the mags.

Left mag: drop of 70, smooth as a sewing machine.

Right mag: the tach gives up 240 RPM and the engine shakes like a dog coming out of a lake. It is not subtle. Grant's pen stops moving.

Back to both. Smooth again, like nothing happened. The book says 175 maximum drop, 50 maximum split. You are 65 over the first number and 170 over the second, and the roughness wasn't a number at all.

<div class="pax-quote">"Everything okay over there? That felt like a thing."</div>

The AWOS keeps murmuring about the temperature on the second radio. The sock at midfield lifts, considers, drops.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You run the fouled-plug drill: 2,000 RPM, lean it hard for a minute, let the heat scour the plugs, then recheck the mags." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: ran the lean burn-off drill"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You run the same check again, unchanged. Maybe it was a one-time thing." "Runup_Again">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: reran the check as-is"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You work the problem methodically first: both mags individually, twice each, watching the JPI for which cylinders go quiet, before you change anything." "Runup_Compare">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: compared both mags on the JPI"])>>
  <<set $methodical to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. You taxi back to the tie-downs and shut down. Whatever this is, you'd rather think about it without paying fuel for the privilege." "Runup_Shutdown">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: taxied back and shut down"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "E. There's an A&P's cell number on the maintenance hangar door. You saw it at the fuel pump, and you idle down and call it right from the pad." "Runup_CallAP">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D1: called the A&P number from the pad"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Runup_Again [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reran the check unchanged: 235, still rough"])>>

Same power, same switch, same thumb. The right mag gives back 235 this time, with the same shudder through the airframe, the same ragged edge in the exhaust note. Back on both, and the engine is all reassurance again, which is somehow less reassuring.

Two data points, both bad, neither explained. The fuel you burned finding that out was not large. The information was not large either.

<div class="pax-quote">"Is that the same thing it did before? It sounded like the same thing."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Now you run the fouled-plug drill: lean it aggressively at 2,000 for a minute and recheck." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then ran the burn-off drill"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You taxi back and shut down. The run-up pad is a bad conference room." "Runup_Shutdown">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then shut down to think"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You call the A&P number from the maintenance hangar door, engine idling." "Runup_CallAP">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then called the A&P"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Runup_Compare [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["JPI comparison: right mag drops EGT on 3 and 5"])>>

You give it the discipline you'd want from yourself on a checkride. Left mag alone: every EGT bar on the JPI rises evenly, the drop is 70, the engine hums. Right mag alone: cylinders three and five go cold on the display, the drop is 240, and the shake is the engine trying to run around two dead holes.

That's not nothing. On the right mag, the plugs it fires in three and five aren't lighting. Fouling would explain it. So would a harness problem on those leads. So would a magneto that is beginning to die from the inside, arcing where it shouldn't, worse when it's hot. The JPI can tell you where. It cannot tell you why.

<div class="pax-quote">"You've got that look Leah gets doing the taxes. What are we learning?"</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You run the lean burn-off drill and recheck. If it's fouling, this cures it, and the JPI will confirm the cure." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then ran the burn-off drill"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You shut down at the tie-downs. You have a diagnosis-shaped hole and a phone." "Runup_Shutdown">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then shut down to think"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Runup_CallAP [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Called the A&P: voicemail"])>>
<<set $vmNote to true>>

The number rings four times through your headset and goes to a voicemail greeting recorded by a man who clearly resents voicemail. At the tone you describe it: Saratoga, right mag, 240 drop with roughness, high DA, leaned taxi, does it sound like fouling or should you worry. You leave your number twice.

It is Sunday in Alpine. The greeting did not promise anything, and neither did the silence after you hung up.

<div class="pax-quote">"Sunday. Even the good ones fish on Sunday."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You run the lean burn-off drill while you wait: 2,000 RPM, lean hard, a minute of heat, recheck." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then ran the burn-off drill"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You taxi back and shut down to wait for the callback in the shade." "Runup_Shutdown">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then shut down to wait"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Runup_Burnoff [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Burn-off drill: recheck shows 120 drop, smooth"])>>

At the pad you set 2,000 RPM and pull the mixture back until the engine complains, then a whisker richer. You hold it there while the EGTs climb and the desert shimmer boils off the cowling, sixty long seconds of heat doing what heat does to lead deposits. Grant watches the tach the way he probably watches a witness.

Mixture back to where it belongs. Mag check.

Left: 70, smooth. Right: 120, and smooth. <<if $methodical>>On the JPI, three and five stay lit this time, their bars dropping evenly with the rest.<</if>> The split is 50 on the nose. The book allows 175 and 50. You are, by the numbers, within limits.

Ninety seconds ago this engine shook like a wet dog on one of its two ignition systems. Right now it would pass any checkride in the country. Both of those things are true, and only one of them fits in a logbook remark.

<<link "Both of you heard it. Time to decide what it means." "Decide_Hub">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Runup_Shutdown [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Shut down at the tie-downs to think"])>>

You taxi back, swing the tail around out of everyone's way (there is no one), and pull the mixture. The prop clunks to a stop and the big engine ticks as it cools, which out here it will take its time doing. The silence afterward is enormous. Somewhere a windmill creaks.

Grant climbs out when you do, stretches his back, and leans against the strut on the shady side with the posture of a man deliberately not saying anything yet. On the ramp, heat comes up through your shoe soles. The maintenance hangar is padlocked. The city office window says CLOSED in stick-on letters. Sunday.

What you know: the right mag dropped 240 with real roughness<<if $methodical>>, and the JPI says cylinders three and five are the ones going dark on it<</if>>. What you don't know is why.

<div class="choice-list">
<<if not $vmNote>>\
<<link "A. You call the A&P number from the maintenance hangar door and leave the whole story on his voicemail." "Ground_VMWait">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Called the A&P from the ramp"])>>
  <<set $vmNote to true>>
<</link>>
<</if>>\
<<link "B. You get the cowl access open and pull a bottom plug from a right-mag cylinder yourself. You carry the wrench for a reason." "Ground_PlugPull">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pulled a plug to look"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You restart, taxi out, and run the lean burn-off drill: if it's fouling, a minute of heat should prove it." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Restarted and ran the burn-off drill"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. You call it. Tonight the airplane sleeps here, and Monday a mechanic looks at it. Everything else is logistics." "Ground_Overnight_Decide">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Decided to stay the night"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ground_VMWait [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Voicemail left; waiting in the shade"])>>

Four rings, the resentful greeting, the tone. You give it to him clean: Saratoga, right mag, 240 and rough, leaned taxi, high DA, fouling or worry. Number, twice.

Then you stand in the wing's shade with Grant and wait for a callback that does not come. Ten minutes. The AWOS says the temperature dropped one degree, which out here counts as weather.

<div class="pax-quote">"While we wait for a stranger to not call back: walk me through it. What are the possible causes, and what does each one do to us?"</div>

It's a fair question, asked the way he asks everything, and answering it out loud organizes your own head whether you want it to or not: fouling, cured by heat and proven by a recheck; a bad plug or harness lead, intermittent by nature; a magneto beginning to break down internally, which likes heat, hides at idle, and does not care what the book number is.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You restart and run the burn-off drill. Whatever else is true, that experiment is free and its result means something." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ran the burn-off drill after the wait"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You pull a bottom plug from a right-mag cylinder and look with your own eyes." "Ground_PlugPull">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pulled a plug after the wait"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You make the overnight call now, while the decision still belongs entirely to you." "Ground_Overnight_Decide">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Chose the overnight from the ramp"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ground_PlugPull [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pulled a bottom plug: it looks ordinary"])>>
<<set $plugPulled to true>>

Cowl access open, a burned knuckle you'll notice tomorrow, and the bottom plug from number five comes out into your palm. You hold it up in the good desert light while Grant peers over your shoulder like the world's best-paid apprentice.

It looks like a spark plug. Tan-gray around the insulator, electrodes worn but honest, one small bead of lead you can flick off with a thumbnail. Not the caked, bridged, fouled monster that would have closed the case. Not pristine either. A plug you'd photograph for no jury on earth.

<div class="pax-quote">"For the record, I have no idea what I'm looking at. But you were hoping it would look worse, weren't you? Worse would have been an answer."</div>

He's exactly right, which is becoming a theme. A fouled plug proves fouling. An ordinary plug proves nothing in either direction: the fouling could be on the other plug this mag fires in that cylinder, or in number three, or the problem could never have been fouling at all.

You torque it back in, safety the lead, close up.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You restart and run the burn-off drill. The recheck numbers still mean what they mean." "Runup_Burnoff">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ran the drill after the plug inspection"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You've seen enough ambiguity for one Sunday. Overnight, and a mechanic Monday." "Ground_Overnight_Decide">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Overnight after the plug inspection"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Decide_Hub [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["The argument at the run-up pad"])>>

You idle there with the engine warm and legal and the sun leaning west. Grant has been composing quietly, and now he delivers, in the reasonable register that has undone better-prepared people than you.

<div class="pax-quote">"Let me lay out the case, and then I'll shut up, because you're the pilot and I'm cargo with opinions. One: your handbook publishes a limit. One-seventy-five, fifty split. You're at one-twenty and fifty. Inside the book, on both counts. Two: you ran the exact procedure for a fouled plug, and the result behaved exactly the way the fouling story predicts. <<if $plugPulled>>Three: you pulled a plug looking for the villain and found a plug. If the evidence for staying were strong, finding it wouldn't be this hard. <</if>>You leaned the taxi at seven thousand six hundred feet of density altitude; you told me yourself that's the classic setup. And the practical side: it's a hundred degrees, this field is closed, the mechanic is voicemail, home is under two hours away in daylight the whole way, and I'm in front of a federal judge at eight."</div>

<div class="pax-quote">"So here's my actual question, and I mean it as a question. What observation would change your mind that we haven't already made? Because if the answer is 'none, but I'm uneasy,' I'd want to know how many flights you've launched feeling uneasy about weather that turned out fine. I'm not asking you to skip a step. I'm asking whether there's a step left."</div>

He turns his palms up: your witness. The engine idles, warm and smooth and within limits, and offers no testimony either way.

The honest inventory: the numbers are legal. The diagnosis is unproven. The route's worst stretch comes first, the engine is heat-soaked, and the fault, if there is a fault, showed itself exactly once and only when things were hot.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. The numbers are the numbers. You take runway 19 now, while the whole flight fits in daylight." "Launch_Hot">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: launched immediately, heat-soaked"])>>
  <<set $heatSoak to true>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. There is a step left: you fly it. One lap of a test profile overhead the field, gear down runway made, watching that mag under real load before you bet the empty country on it." "Test_Profile">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: flew a test profile overhead first"])>>
  <<set $tested to true>>
<</link>>

<<if not $plugPulled>>\
<<link "C. You shut down and pull a bottom plug from a right-mag cylinder. Physical evidence beats inference." "Ground_PlugPull">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: shut down to pull a plug"])>>
<</link>>
<</if>>\
<<link "D. You park it in the shade for ninety minutes. Cooler air, cooler engine, a recheck when the sun quits fighting, and still enough twilight to get home." "Delay_Cooldown">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: waited out the heat"])>>
  <<set $delayed to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "E. You call it here: the airplane stays, a mechanic sees it Monday, and tonight you buy your brother-in-law dinner in Alpine." "Ground_Overnight_Decide">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D2: chose the overnight"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Delay_Cooldown [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Waited 90 minutes for the cool"])>>

You shut down at the tie-downs and declare a recess. Grant takes it better than his calendar does: he sets up his deposition notes on the pilot lounge's one card table (the door code is on the door frame, small-field style) and works while you drink vending-machine water and watch the shadows get long.

<<if $vmNote and not $vmReply>>\
<<set $vmReply to true>>\
At 6:20 your phone buzzes. Not a call: a text, from the A&P's number.

<div class="text-msg">Heard vm. If it cleared after a hard lean burnoff its prob plug fouling, that field eats plugs in summer. But a 240 with real shake and a 50 split after, I'd want that mag on a bench before too many more hot starts. Heat brings that kind of thing out. Cant get there till tues am. Yr call.</div>

Grant reads it over your shoulder, twice, and for once says nothing while he thinks.

<div class="pax-quote">"Well. He agrees with both of us. That's the least helpful document I've seen all year."</div>
<</if>>\
By 6:45 the AWOS has surrendered eight degrees and the light has gone amber. The engine cowl is cool enough to rest a hand on. A recheck now is a recheck of a cold, rested engine in kinder air: it tells you about this minute, not about the minute you'll be over Altuda Pass at full power.

Wheels-up by 7:00 puts you home at 8:50, official sunset 8:52, twilight to 9:19. The margin fits, if nothing asks it not to.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Runup once more, and if it's clean, you go: cooler engine, cooler air, softer light, same book." "Launch_Cooled">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: launched after the cool-down"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Runup once more, and even if it's clean, you fly the test profile overhead before setting out. Twilight math be damned." "Test_Profile">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: test profile even after cooling"])>>
  <<set $tested to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. The cool-down changed the temperature, not the diagnosis. Overnight, mechanic Monday." "Ground_Overnight_Decide">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["D3: overnight after the cool-down"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Launch_Hot [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Departed runway 19 at 5:15, engine heat-soaked"])>>

You brief it like you mean it: runway 19, left turn on course, and if anything sounds like anything below a thousand feet you are landing on whatever is left in front of you. Grant nods once, all business now that the verdict is in.

The density altitude makes the takeoff roll a long story with a slow ending. N429TC finally flies at the six-hundred-foot markers you never normally meet, and the climb is the mountain-west special: a thousand-horse engine's sound with a lawn-chair rate. The oil temp sits high and thinks about sitting higher. Nothing misses. Nothing shakes. The right mag keeps whatever opinions it has to itself.

At 8,500 the town slides behind the nose and the country opens up ahead: the Glass Mountains' brown shoulders, the two-lane to Marathon, and after that the kind of emptiness that makes the fuel gauges feel personal.

<<link "You pick your line east and settle in for the climb to 9,500." "Climb_Out">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Launch_Cooled [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Departed at 7:00 after the cool-down, runup clean"])>>

The recheck comes back clean twice: 70 left, 95 right, split of 25, smooth both ways. A cold engine in kind air, telling you about this minute.

Runway 19 in the amber light, and the airplane flies like the evening was built for it: the DA has surrendered a thousand feet, the climb is honest, the oil temp behaves. Alpine shrinks behind you into its bowl of hills. Grant watches the desert go gold and, for the first time since the run-up pad, lets the legal pad sleep.

<div class="pax-quote">"For what it's worth, waiting was a version of rigor too. I bill by the hour; I understand paying for certainty."</div>

Sunset is 8:52. Home around 8:50, twilight in your pocket. The numbers all fit, provided every one of them holds.

<<link "You climb to 9,500 and take up the line for home." "Climb_Out">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Climb_Out [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Routing decision leaving Alpine"])>>

Passing through 9,000 with the trim earning its keep, the routing question is still yours to answer. The GPS's magenta line runs direct: over the Altuda saddle, north of Marathon, then the long empty diagonal to Ozona. Shortest, highest, loneliest. The alternative bends the first half north to ride the I-10 corridor past Fort Stockton: twenty-five extra miles that keep a seven-thousand-foot runway and a paved road inside gliding conversation for the worst stretch. <<if not $delayed and not $tested>>There's a third shape, too: a climbing circle overhead the field first, ten minutes of full-power scrutiny with a runway directly below, before committing to any line at all.<</if>>

<<if $delayed>>The light is amber going on copper, and the extra miles would spend twilight you counted as margin.<<else>>The sun is high enough that time is the cheapest thing on board.<</if>>

<div class="pax-quote">"I'll pretend I didn't see the shorter one if you pretend the judge won't notice eight-oh-five."</div>

He says it lightly. It lands the way everything he says lands.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Direct. It's why you bought a fast airplane, and the numbers passed." "Cruise_Entry">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Routing: direct over the high country"])>>
  <<set $routing to "direct">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. The corridor. You bend north for I-10 and Fort Stockton and buy outs with minutes." "Cruise_Entry">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Routing: I-10 corridor via Fort Stockton"])>>
  <<set $routing to "corridor">>
<</link>>

<<if not $delayed and not $tested>>\
<<link "C. Overhead first. You spiral up over the field and give the engine ten minutes at full power with a runway under you before you go anywhere." "Climb_Overhead">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Routing: full-power scrutiny overhead first"])>>
  <<set $routing to "overhead">>
<</link>>
<</if>>\
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Climb_Overhead [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Climbing circles overhead E38 at full power"])>>
<<set $tested to true>>

You tell Grant the plan in one sentence and he answers with a lawyer's favorite word: "Noted." The Saratoga carves a wide climbing circle over the field, full power, mixture where the JPI likes it, the runway rotating slowly below like a held breath.

Six minutes in, passing 10,200, the engine stumbles.

Not a cough: a stagger, three or four cycles of it, the airframe buzzing with misfire, the JPI's three and five bars flickering like bad neon. Then it smooths, as if embarrassed. Ten seconds of honesty from somewhere under the cowl.

<<set $missBegan to true>><<set $grantSaw to true>>\
<div class="pax-quote">"Okay. I heard that one with my own ears. Case dismissed."</div>

The field is directly below you. Every option in the world, and all of them downhill.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You pull the power back to a gentle cruise setting and spiral down to land at Alpine. The airplane just testified." "Ground_AfterCatch">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed back at E38 after the stumble"])>>
  <<set $divert to "E38">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Fort Stockton is 51 miles, and it's where the nearest open shop will be Monday. You could reposition it there now, gently, while the daylight is deep." "Reposition_KFST">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Repositioned to KFST after the stumble"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Test_Profile [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Flying the test profile overhead E38"])>>

You brief it to Grant as a flight with a runway attached: up over the field, full power in the climb to nine and a half, three minutes of sustained cruise power, a mag isolation at altitude with the field made, and only then a decision about the empty country. He listens, asks one question ("What would failing look like?"), and writes your answer on the legal pad like an exhibit.

Runway 19, the long high-DA roll, and the climbing circles begin. The field turns beneath the wing. Full power, temps high but legal, the JPI steady.

<<if $delayed>>\
The evening engine gives you nothing to see. The climb is clean, the sustained power is clean, and the isolation at 9,500 shows the left at its usual 70-equivalent and the right holding smooth, three and five lit and even. Ten minutes of interrogation, no confession.
<<link "The profile is flown and the witness held up. Decision time, overhead the field." "Decide_AfterTest">><</link>>
<<else>>\
Seven minutes in, at sustained cruise power with the temps at their afternoon worst, the engine staggers: a run of misfire you feel in the rudder pedals, the JPI's three and five bars sagging and flickering, four long seconds, then smooth as if nothing. On the isolation check that follows, the right mag alone is rough enough that your hand goes back to BOTH without asking your brain.
<<set $missBegan to true>><<set $grantSaw to true>><<set $testShowedDrop to true>>\

<div class="pax-quote">"I saw the little bars do it. You don't have to say anything. I retract the whole argument."</div>

The field is right below, patient as ever.
<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You spiral down and land at Alpine. The test did its one job." "Ground_AfterCatch">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed back at E38 after the test caught it"])>>
  <<set $divert to "E38">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You point it at Fort Stockton, 51 gentle miles, where the shop is. Reposition now, while the fault is a stagger and not a promise." "Reposition_KFST">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Repositioned to KFST after the test caught it"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>
</div>
<</if>>\

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Decide_AfterTest [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Test flown clean; deciding overhead the field"])>>

You level the wings overhead Alpine with the test flown and the engine's slate clean. This is what buying evidence looks like when the evidence cooperates: ten minutes of fuel, a small ache in your neck from watching the JPI, and an engine that did everything right under exactly the loads you were worried about.

<div class="pax-quote">"For the record, counselor: you tested it, it passed, and I watched. Whatever you decide next, that was the right ten minutes."</div>

The line home waits. So does the option nobody would blame you for.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You set course from here, direct, 9,500, home before the light goes." "Cruise_Entry">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Set course for home off the clean test"])>>
  <<set $routing to "direct">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You ride the I-10 corridor anyway. The test bought confidence, not certainty, and the outs are cheap." "Cruise_Entry">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Corridor routing even after the clean test"])>>
  <<set $routing to "corridor">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You land back and keep the airplane here for the mechanic anyway. The test was for the mechanic's benefit, not the flight's." "Ground_Overnight_Decide">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed back; overnight despite the clean test"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Entry [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Established in cruise eastbound"])>>

<<if $routing is "corridor">>Level 9,500 on the northern bend, Fort Stockton's grid crawling up under the left wing in its own good time, I-10's bead of trucks keeping you company off the nose. The extra miles ride along quietly, the way insurance does.<<else>>Level 9,500 on the direct line, the Altuda saddle sliding under and the last paved road for a while going with it. The country below is the color of an old saddle and about as soft.<</if>> Fuel where it should be, JPI bars even, the autopilot holding the line while you keep the engine company with your ears.

<<if $delayed or ($tested and not $missBegan)>>\
<<link "The miles start coming off the total." "Cruise_Smooth">><</link>>
<<else>>\
<<link "The miles start coming off the total." "Cruise_Miss">><</link>>
<</if>>\

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Smooth [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise: the engine keeps its own counsel"])>>

The engine settles into the long steady pull that eats distance without drama. <<if $routing is "corridor">>Fort Stockton comes and goes off the wing, its runway a pale stripe you are quietly glad not to need.<<else>>Marathon's grid comes and goes, small as a circuit board dropped in the desert.<</if>> Grant reads his notes, then doesn't, then watches Texas turn evening-colored at two and a half miles a minute.

<<if $vmNote and not $vmReply>>\
<<set $vmReply to true>>\
Over the emptiest stretch, your phone finds one bar of something and buzzes against your leg. A text, from the A&P's number, sent to the Sunday air:

<div class="text-msg">Heard vm. If it cleared after a hard lean burnoff its prob plug fouling, that field eats plugs in summer. But a 240 with real shake and a 50 split after, I'd want that mag on a bench before too many more hot starts. Heat brings that kind of thing out. Cant get there till tues am. Yr call.</div>

You read it twice. Behind you, the field where the bench is. Ahead, home. The engine, consulted, says nothing new.
<</if>>\
Abeam Sanderson, 9,500, the JPI bars even as a picket fence, a thought arrives and sets up camp: you could check the mags right now. In cruise, at altitude, a two-second flick each way would tell you how the right one feels about the last hour of heat. Some pilots do it as habit on long legs. Others won't disturb a running system over country like this on principle, and the POH, for what it's worth, calls for the check at run-up and says nothing about cruise.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You check: left, both, right, both, eyes on the tach and the JPI." "Cruise_MagCheckBeat">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise: ran an in-flight mag check"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You leave it alone. The engine is smooth, the country is empty, and the check can live at the next run-up where it belongs." "Arrive_KHYI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise: left the running system alone"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You split the difference: no switching, but you shallow the leaning, log the JPI numbers, and watch three and five like they owe you money." "Arrive_KHYI">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise: watched the JPI, touched nothing"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_MagCheckBeat [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["In-flight check: right mag clean at cruise"])>>

You tell Grant what you're doing before you do it, which he appreciates more than he says. Left alone: the faintest softening, all bars even. Both. Right alone: you brace for it, and the engine gives you two seconds of perfectly ordinary running, three and five as lit as anything. Both again.

Clean. A cool engine at sixty-five percent power in evening air, telling you about this minute. You knew that's all it could testify to before you asked. You asked anyway, and the answer is worth exactly what it cost.

<div class="pax-quote">"I understood maybe a third of that. The third I understood seemed like good news."</div>

<<link "The last hundred miles are the gentle ones." "Arrive_KHYI">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Arrive_KHYI [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Arrival at San Marcos"])>>

The land steps down through Junction and the Hill Country goes soft and green-brown in the last light. San Marcos tower is awake and bored. <<if $delayed>>The sun sets somewhere over your left shoulder on downwind, official to the minute, and the runway lights come up like the field is setting a table.<<else>>The evening is still ahead of the sun when the tower clears you in.<</if>>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You take the straight-in they offer for 26 and keep the power settings you trust." "End_Home_Arrived">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Accepted the straight-in"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You ask for the overhead teardrop to a full pattern: one more minute aloft, one more stable look at everything, in exchange for nothing you'll miss." "End_Home_Arrived">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Flew the full pattern by choice"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Miss [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Cruise: the right mag begins to miss"])>>
<<set $missBegan to true>>

Thirty-eight minutes out of Alpine, the engine misses.

One beat, like a skipped heartbeat in a chest you're leaning against. Then a run of them: a buzzing stagger through the airframe, the tach needle shivering, the JPI's three and five bars flickering down and up. Four seconds, maybe five. Then smooth again, the engine pretending none of it happened.

<<if $routing is "corridor">>Fort Stockton's runway sits fifteen miles off the left wing, long and pale and open for business to anyone with a radio call. I-10 runs under you like a handrail.<<else>>Below is the country you briefed as the memory of airports: Marathon behind the left wing somewhere, Sanderson's canyons ahead, the last paved road a rumor to the south. Fort Stockton is sixty miles behind the left shoulder. Ozona is a hundred ahead.<</if>>

Grant's pen has stopped. He doesn't say anything. His silence has excellent diction.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You isolate it now: a deliberate mag check at altitude, left, both, right, both, and learn which system is lying." "Cruise_Isolate">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Miss: isolated with an in-flight mag check"])>>
  <<set $isolated to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You go richer, boost pump on, switch tanks, carb-and-fuel logic first. Rule out the cheap causes before touching the ignition." "Cruise_Fiddle">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Miss: chased fuel causes first"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You turn for the nearest long runway right now and diagnose from overhead it, not from out here." "Divert_Hub">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Miss: turned for the outs immediately"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. It cleared. Engines do this. You hold what you have and give it a minute to be a fluke." "Cruise_PressOn">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Miss: pressed on, calling it a fluke"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Fiddle [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Fuel logic changed nothing"])>>

Mixture richer: the EGTs drop, the miss doesn't care. Boost pump: pressure needle unmoved, the stagger returns for another four-second run while the pump whines. Other tank: the engine drinks from it identically. You've spent three minutes and ruled out the cheap suspects, which is worth something, and fixed nothing, which is worth knowing.

The airplane flies on through it, autopilot indifferent, altitude pegged. The misses come in little paragraphs now, thirty seconds apart, then a clean minute, then another paragraph.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You isolate the ignition: left, both, right, both, and get a name for this." "Cruise_Isolate">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then isolated the mags"])>>
  <<set $isolated to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You turn for the nearest long runway and do the rest of your thinking pointed at it." "Divert_Hub">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then turned for the outs"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. It runs. It keeps clearing. You press on and keep the troubleshooting in your lap." "Cruise_PressOn">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Then pressed on anyway"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Isolate [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Isolation: it's the right mag, airborne"])>>

You announce it to Grant in five words and do it like a lab procedure. Left mag alone: the engine softens a hair and runs like silk. Back to both. Right mag alone: the stagger arrives on cue, deep and immediate, three and five collapsing on the display, and your hand is back on BOTH before the second shudder finishes.

There's your name. The right magneto, the one that shook the airplane on the ground and got talked back into the flight by a clean recheck, is failing under heat, airborne, over this.

On the left mag alone the engine is smooth. On both, the right one joins in just often enough to shake the airframe and your composure on its own schedule.

<div class="pax-quote">"Translate?" A beat while you do. "Okay. So the spare works. What I want to say is 'then we're fine.' The fact that you're not saying it is the whole conversation, isn't it."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You select the left mag alone, smooth the engine out, and turn for the nearest long runway with your remaining redundancy spent on purpose." "Divert_Hub">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Left mag only, turned for the outs"])>>
  <<set $singleMag to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You keep BOTH selected, accept the intermittent shake, and turn for the nearest long runway with the sick mag still contributing what it can." "Divert_Hub">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Kept both mags, turned for the outs"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. You select the left mag alone, the engine runs smooth as new, and home is 170 miles of smooth away. This is what redundancy is for." "Cruise_PressOn">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Left mag only, continued for home"])>>
  <<set $singleMag to true>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Divert_Hub [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Choosing the out"])>>

You put the destination question where it belongs: on the chart in front of you, not in the calendar behind you.

<<if $routing is "corridor">>Fort Stockton is the easy geometry, fifteen-odd miles, 7,508 feet of runway, the AWOS already legible, a descent you could fly with one hand writing the logbook entry. Ozona sits a hundred miles ahead on course; Alpine is eighty behind, over the high country you just crossed.<<else>>From out here the honest options are all commitments. Fort Stockton: sixty miles back over the left shoulder, big runway, the only shop in the region come Monday. Ozona: a hundred miles ahead on course, six thousand feet of quiet asphalt, and every mile toward it is also a mile toward home. Alpine: eighty-five miles back through the saddle, into the lowering sun.<</if>> Albuquerque Center is a button-push away on 135.875, and the word "precautionary" is free to say and cheap to own.

<div class="pax-quote">"Whatever you pick, pick it like I'm not here. I can be mad at a magneto. I'd have real trouble being mad at you."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Fort Stockton. Long runway, the Monday shop, and the shortest version of this story." "Approach_KFST">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to KFST"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KFST">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Ozona. On course, long enough, and it converts the divert into most of the trip." "Approach_KOZA">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverted to KOZA"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KOZA">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. Back to Alpine. The devil you know, the tie-down you left, the mechanic's Tuesday bench." "Divert_E38">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turned back for E38"])>>
  <<set $divert to "E38">>
<</link>>

<<link "D. None of them. The engine is holding; home holds the calendar. You continue." "Cruise_PressOn">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Declined every out"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_PressOn [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressing on; Ozona is the next mile marker"])>>

<<if $singleMag>>On the left mag alone the engine runs like a promise, smooth in a way that would be comforting if you didn't know what bought it. The tachometer holds. The JPI is a picket fence again. Somewhere in the right magneto, whatever is broken rides along at four hundred and some RPM of its own, disconnected and patient.<<else>>The engine runs its new pattern: a clean minute, then a paragraph of misfire that buzzes the airframe and flickers three and five, then clean again. You find yourself counting the clean minutes the way you'd count contractions.<</if>>

The land starts its long step down. Ozona's water tower and its quiet runway crawl up the windshield and sit off the nose, six thousand feet of asphalt, the last easy answer between here and the Hill Country. <<if $delayed>>The light has gone from amber to ember.<<else>>The sun is low enough now to sit in the mirrors.<</if>>

<div class="pax-quote">"That's the one you mentioned, isn't it. Ozona." A pause with structure to it. "I'm not arguing anymore. I'm just reading the exhibits out loud."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You take it. Ozona, now, while the choice is still entirely yours." "Approach_KOZA">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Took Ozona, the last easy out"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KOZA">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Junction is only fifty more miles, I-10 the whole way, and home fifty behind it. You continue." "Cruise_Deeper">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Passed Ozona, continuing"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Deeper [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Past Ozona; the situation chooses a direction"])>>

<<if $singleMag>>\
The left mag carries the airplane past Ozona without a stumble, and the miles to Junction come off in that smooth, expensive silence. The panel lights are on now. Below, ranch lights arrive in ones and twos, the country slowly remembering people. Junction's beacon shows up right on schedule, white-green against the dusk, I-10 pouring headlights past it.

Fifty miles beyond it, home. You have one ignition system doing all the work, one doing none, night arriving, and an airplane that has been flawless for an hour on exactly half its redundancy.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Junction, tonight. The airplane sleeps at KJCT, and tomorrow it's a two-hour problem instead of a headline." "End_KJCT_Dusk">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Stopped at Junction for the night"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KJCT">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Fifty miles. Twenty minutes. The left mag has earned the benefit of the doubt. You continue home." "End_PressOn_Landed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued home on the left mag"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>
<<else>>\
Past Ozona the misfire paragraphs get longer and lose their manners. The clean minutes shrink to clean half-minutes. Twice the engine sags, actually sags, a couple hundred RPM of stagger that pushes the nose down a degree before it catches itself, and the second time Grant's hand finds the door armrest and stays there.

The JPI has stopped being subtle: three and five live somewhere south of their neighbors now, flickering. The airframe buzz is intermittent but familiar, a phone ringing in another room that you keep almost answering.

Junction's beacon is twenty miles ahead. The last of the light is going. The engine runs, then doesn't quite, then does.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You finally do the isolation you've been owed for an hour: left mag alone." "Cruise_LateIsolate">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Late isolation to the left mag"])>>
  <<set $isolated to true>>
  <<set $singleMag to true>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Junction, now, while the engine still makes climb power on request." "End_KJCT_Dusk">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Took Junction while the taking was good"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KJCT">>
<</link>>

<<link "C. It keeps catching itself. Fifty miles past Junction is home. You press on as-is." "Cruise_Failing">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Pressed past Junction, engine degrading"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>
<</if>>\

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_LateIsolate [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Left mag alone: smooth at last"])>>

Left mag, alone. The engine smooths out mid-shudder, like a hand laid on a rattling table. The picket fence rebuilds itself on the JPI. It is the sound you could have had an hour ago, and knowing that is its own instrument reading.

Junction's beacon holds off the nose, its runway lights a small punctuation in the gathering dark. Home is fifty miles past it. One system working, one confirmed sick, and the night coming up to meet you.

<div class="pax-quote">"Better." A pause. "Better isn't the same as good, is it. I can hear the difference now."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Junction. You land while every option is still open and let tomorrow be tomorrow." "End_KJCT_Dusk">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Landed Junction after the late isolation"])>>
  <<set $divert to "KJCT">>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Smooth is smooth. Twenty minutes to home. You continue." "End_PressOn_Landed">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Continued home after the late isolation"])>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
  <<set $pressOn to $pressOn + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Cruise_Failing [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Past Junction; the engine stops negotiating"])>>

Junction's lights slide behind the left wing and become the past. For six or seven minutes the engine keeps its ugly bargain, roughness and recovery, roughness and recovery, while the ranch country west of the Hill Country goes fully dark below, stars on top and the occasional yard light beneath, and not much in between.

Then the bargain ends. The sag comes and doesn't catch itself: the engine drops into a deep, continuous stagger, EGTs scattering, manifold pressure available but the fire behind it arriving in fits. You are holding 7,000 with maybe sixty percent of an engine on a good second, and the seconds are not all good.

The nose is already trimmed down before you decide anything. Some part of you has been briefing this without permission: the dark quilt below, the gray thread of a caliche ranch road running northeast, wide as forgiveness, and Fredericksburg's glow twenty-some miles too far ahead.

<div class="pax-quote">"Tell me what to do with my hands and I'll do it."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You fly the airplane to the road while power remains to choose with: flaps set, into what wind there is, gear a deliberate decision, flashlight in Grant's fist." "End_RanchRoad">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Committed to the ranch road under control"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Fredericksburg's glow is twenty miles. The engine keeps almost recovering. You stretch for the airport." "End_RanchRoad">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Tried to stretch for the airport glow"])>>
  <<set $stretched to true>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_KFST [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverting to Fort Stockton"])>>

You tell Center the word and the word does its work: "precautionary," and the frequency reorganizes itself around you without a single wasted syllable. Descent at your discretion. The Fort Stockton AWOS robot recites its evening report: wind one seven zero at eight, altimeter three zero zero seven.

<<if $singleMag>>The left mag flies you down the long slope smooth as poured concrete.<<else>>The engine throws in one more paragraph of misfire on the descent, as if to endorse the decision.<</if>> Runway 12/30 shows up pale and enormous, 7,508 feet of it, and you land on 12 with a thousand-foot float's worth of margin and taxi in past hangars shut tight for the weekend.

Engine off. Tick of cooling metal. The Sunday silence of a west Texas ramp, two men, and one magneto with a secret.

Grant is already on his phone rearranging his Monday, voice level, the word "continuance" pronounced like a tool he owns. When he hangs up he looks at the airplane a long moment.

<div class="pax-quote">"For the record: the version of this where you'd listened to me is the version where that happened over the part with no roads. I withdraw my earlier remarks. All of them."</div>

<<link "The rest is phone calls and a shared room at the highway motel." "End_KFST_Precautionary">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Approach_KOZA [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Diverting into Ozona"])>>

Ozona has no one to talk to and needs nothing said: you announce on CTAF to an audience of parked crop sprayers and fly a wide, gentle pattern to runway 16. <<if $singleMag>>The left mag hums you down final without a flicker.<<else>>The misfire keeps its distance for the whole descent, then throws one last shiver on short final, a parting signature.<</if>> Six thousand feet of quiet asphalt accepts the airplane, and the rollout is long and unhurried because you have nowhere better to be than under control.

The ramp is empty except for the courtesy car, which exists after all: a county pickup with the key above the visor and a clipboard asking only that you say who you were.

Grant stands on the ramp in the last usable light, hands in his pockets, looking at the airplane the way people look at horses that almost threw them.

<div class="pax-quote">"I want to say something for the record and then buy you dinner if this town has one. You were inside your book the whole time and you still called it. I make arguments for a living, and the scariest thing I've learned today is how good mine was."</div>

<<link "Chicken-fried steak, a motel with a buzzing sign, and tomorrow made simple." "End_KOZA_Precautionary">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Divert_E38 [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Turning back for Alpine"])>>

The one-eighty puts the low sun in the windshield and the high country back under the nose, which is the price of the familiar tie-down and the Tuesday bench. <<if $singleMag>>The left mag makes it a smooth, golden, uphill-feeling ride, the saddle at Altuda repainting itself in evening colors.<<else>>The misfire comes along for the ride, its paragraphs arriving and dissolving while you cross the saddle with more altitude than you strictly need and no apology for it.<</if>>

Alpine's AWOS is still narrating the temperature to nobody. You land on 19 in long shadows, taxi to the same tie-down whose chains you unhooked three hours and one education ago, and shut it down.

Grant helps with the chains, which he has never once done before, and doesn't say anything clever at all.

<<link "Town is two miles. The motel has vacancies. Monday, this field wakes up with mechanics on it." "End_E38_Return">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Reposition_KFST [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Repositioning gently to Fort Stockton"])>>

You make it the tamest fifty-one miles the airplane has ever flown: reduced power, altitude in hand the whole way, I-10 under the right wing like a spare runway unrolled for the occasion, Center advised in plain words what you're doing and why. The engine, at this kindly power setting in the cooling afternoon, never says a word. <<if $grantSaw>>Grant watches the JPI the entire way, self-appointed to the board of directors of cylinders three and five.<</if>>

Fort Stockton's 7,508 feet arrive under the wheels with the whole affair feeling almost anticlimactic, which was the intended design. You taxi to the maintenance hangar, find its doors shut for Sunday, and leave the airplane nose-to-the-door with a note under the wiper written on legal-pad paper in a lawyer's ruthless print: the symptoms, the numbers, your phone, the word URGENT underlined once, because twice would be shouting.

<<link "The highway motel has two rooms and a view of the interstate." "End_Reposition_KFST">><</link>>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Ground_AfterCatch [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Back on the ground at Alpine, question answered"])>>

The spiral down is unhurried and the landing ordinary, which feels almost rude given the circumstances. You put N429TC back on the same tie-down, and this time the chains go on like a verdict.

The question the run-up couldn't answer is answered: the fault is real, it likes heat and load, and it showed itself the moment you gave it both with a runway underneath. The airplane stays. That part is over, and it was never really the hard part.

The hard part checks his watch, then visibly decides not to. Tomorrow at eight, a federal judge expects him groomed and lethal in San Antonio, 273 miles from this ramp.

<div class="pax-quote">"Options as I see them. One: I find tonight's version of a rental car and drive it. Five hours, ugly, doable. Two: I call opposing counsel tonight, eat the continuance, and owe a man I dislike a favor. Three exists only if this town hides an airline. You know this country; I know my judge. Deal me a recommendation."</div>

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You help him hunt down the rental outfit's after-hours number and get him rolling east tonight with coffee and a full tank." "End_Caught_Overnight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Got Grant a car and rolling east"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You tell him to make the call and eat the continuance: tired driving five hours of two-lane in the dark is the same bet you just refused to make with the airplane." "End_Caught_Overnight">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Advised the continuance over the night drive"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_E38_Return [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: back where the day started, on purpose"])>>

The motel clerk recognizes the look of you both and doesn't ask. Dinner is green chile and quiet. Monday morning the field wakes up with mechanics on it after all, and by ten the right magneto is open on a bench with a carbon track across the distributor block, scorched in like a signature. "Heat-soaked climb at altitude," the mechanic says, tapping it. "This thing was always going to introduce itself properly today. You just picked where."

Grant's deposition moves to Wednesday. He bills the drive home Tuesday to the client with a straight face and buys the new distributor block himself, over your objection, "as a licensing fee for the story."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The fault waited until you were airborne over the high country, and you spent it the most conservative way available: a one-eighty back to the field you knew, with the sun still up and altitude in hand, and a bench the next morning that confirmed everything.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Turning back reads as defeat and functions as engineering: Alpine held your tie-down, Monday mechanics, a town you could walk to, and terrain you'd just seen in daylight. The alternative math (pressing to somewhere new because it's ahead) values motion over information. The one hard look this path deserves: the ride back crossed the saddle again with a misbehaving ignition system, and a case existed for Fort Stockton's bigger runway and shop. You weighed known against nearer. Reasonable seats disagree here; yours decided, which is the job.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Exactly what the one-eighty always looks like when it's flown early: boring. The engine got kinder power, the terrain got more altitude than pride would have carried, and the decision was made while every option was still open rather than after two more misses closed some. The 180 is a system, not an apology.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The turn back is a destination choice like any other. Fly it before the airplane makes it for you, and let the bench write the last word.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readField to false>><<set $methodical to false>><<set $vmNote to false>><<set $vmReply to false>><<set $plugPulled to false>><<set $tested to false>><<set $testShowedDrop to false>><<set $delayed to false>><<set $heatSoak to false>><<set $missBegan to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $stretched to false>><<set $isolated to false>><<set $singleMag to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $pressOn to 0>><<set $grantSaw to false>><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_KOZA_Precautionary [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: Ozona, under control, by choice"])>>

The county pickup starts on the second try and the diner in town serves chicken-fried steak until eight. Grant moves his deposition by phone from the booth, performing contrition he does not feel, and tips like a man renegotiating with the universe. The motel sign buzzes. The stars are ridiculous.

Tuesday, the mobile mechanic out of San Angelo puts the right mag on his tailgate bench and finds the carbon track inside twenty minutes. "Y'all flew the smart half of this one," he says, which out here is a eulogy-grade compliment. N429TC is home Wednesday. The county gets its pickup back with a full tank and a note.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>When the engine started editorializing, you took the out that was also progress: Ozona, on course, six thousand feet of runway, reached with power to spare and daylight in hand. The mission converted into a phone call and a motel, which is the entire design goal of a precautionary landing.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p><<if $isolated>>The in-flight isolation gave the problem its name before you bet anything on geography, and the divert spent that knowledge well.<<else>>You diverted without a full diagnosis, which trades some information for time and margin; over that country, an entirely defensible exchange rate.<</if>> <<if $pressOn gte 1>>The miles flown between the first miss and this decision were the expensive ones: nothing on the panel got better during them, and the options behind you got farther away.<<else>>The decision came early, while every option was still open, which is what early is for.<</if>> Grant's line on the ramp is the scenario's thesis found by a layman: the argument was good, and the argument was beside the point.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>An on-course divert is the least dramatic instrument in the bag and often the best: it banks the progress, keeps the interstate's services within a courtesy car's reach, and leaves every future option (bench, ferry, airline) alive. The precautionary landing's reputation as an overreaction survives only among pilots who haven't needed one; the NTSB files are quieter on the subject, mostly because precautionary landings don't appear in them.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A divert that's also sixty percent of the trip is no retreat. It's the mission, renegotiated from a position of strength.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readField to false>><<set $methodical to false>><<set $vmNote to false>><<set $vmReply to false>><<set $plugPulled to false>><<set $tested to false>><<set $testShowedDrop to false>><<set $delayed to false>><<set $heatSoak to false>><<set $missBegan to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $stretched to false>><<set $isolated to false>><<set $singleMag to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $pressOn to 0>><<set $grantSaw to false>><</link>>
</div>
<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_KFST_Precautionary [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: Fort Stockton, the short version"])>>

Monday at 8:40 the shop two hangars down rolls its doors open and inherits your Sunday. By eleven the distributor block is on the counter between you, its carbon track catching the fluorescent light. "See how it wanders?" the mechanic says, tracing it with a pen he doesn't let touch the surface. "Cold, spark stays home. Hot, it takes this road. Y'all heard the road."

Grant caught the shop's dawn loaner east and made San Antonio with time to shave twice. The new block goes in before lunch; you're home for dinner Monday, one day and one education late.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The first miss got a named response inside of minutes: the nearest long runway, a word to Center, and a wide pale runway that made the whole problem feel smaller on short final. The shop confirmed the fault the next morning and the trip finished by loaner car and a Monday-evening ferry flight home.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p><<if $routing is "corridor">>The corridor routing wrote this ending before the engine did: fifteen miles to a runway instead of sixty, purchased at the run-up pad for twenty-five extra track miles. That's what buying outs looks like when the bill comes due.<<else>>From the direct line, Fort Stockton cost a turn back toward the sun and the discipline to prefer a known good option behind you over unknown miles ahead. That discipline is the rare commodity. Geometry is just arithmetic.<</if>> The word "precautionary," said early to Center, converted the system from an audience into a resource, and it costs exactly nothing. <<if $singleMag>>Running the left mag alone smoothed the ride down, and spending your remaining redundancy deliberately, pointed at a runway, is the correct shape for that decision.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Divert to capability, not just proximity: 7,508 feet of runway, an AWOS, a shop that would open in fifteen hours, and an interstate for the human logistics. The destination solved the airplane's problem and the calendar's in one landing. That's not luck; that's what the Field Guide page was for.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>The best divert answers tomorrow's question too. Land where the fix lives.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readField to false>><<set $methodical to false>><<set $vmNote to false>><<set $vmReply to false>><<set $plugPulled to false>><<set $tested to false>><<set $testShowedDrop to false>><<set $delayed to false>><<set $heatSoak to false>><<set $missBegan to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $stretched to false>><<set $isolated to false>><<set $singleMag to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $pressOn to 0>><<set $grantSaw to false>><</link>>
</div>
