:: End_PressOn_Landed [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: home on one magneto"])>>

San Marcos tower clears you to land in full dark, and the left magneto, which has now flown an airplane by itself for the better part of two hours, delivers you to runway 26 without a comma out of place. The taxi in is very quiet. Grant doesn't narrate this arrival to anyone.

On the ramp he stands under the wing for a moment before getting his bag. "I've won cases I should have lost," he says finally. "The feeling afterward is exactly this. You don't frame those verdicts."

Thursday the bench finds the carbon track in the right mag's distributor block. Your mechanic calls it a "when, not if" and doesn't ask how the airplane got home. You tell him anyway, because somebody should have to say it out loud.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>A demonstrated ignition failure at altitude was answered with <<if $isolated>>a correct diagnosis and then a long bet: the healthy magneto, alone, across the emptiest country on the route, into the night, past <<if $pressOn gte 3>>every exit the chart offered<<else>>good exits<</if>>.<<else>>continued flight on a degrading system, without ever fully naming the problem, past the exits.<</if>> The bet paid. The airplane is home, the passenger is home, and the margin that got you there existed entirely inside a magneto you had no reason to trust and one you had merely not yet caught lying.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p><<if $isolated>>Split this path in two and grade the halves separately. The isolation was airmanship: deliberate, informative, correctly executed. Everything after it was exposure: single-ignition, night, terrain-poor, help-poor, chosen against multiple runways of refusal.<<else>>The undiagnosed press-on compounds two errors: flying a sick system, and not knowing which system was sick.<</if>> "This is what redundancy is for" is the scenario's most seductive sentence, and it inverts the truth: redundancy exists to get you to the nearest suitable runway after a failure, not to complete missions on the last layer. The moment you select the last healthy system, redundancy is over. What remains is all there is.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>Junction. Ozona. Fort Stockton. The judgment this ending lacks isn't knowledge (you knew) or skill (the flying was fine); it's the willingness to let the calendar lose. The debrief question that matters: what, specifically, would have made you land? If the honest answer is "a second failure," then the plan was to have an emergency. Write the personal minimum now, in a chair, in daylight: known ignition fault equals nearest suitable, full stop.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Landing a bet like this feels like vindication and proves nothing. The bench doesn't care that it worked; next time the bench votes first.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
<<link "Return to Start" "FlightPrep">><<set $pathArray to []>><<set $badchoices to 0>><<set $readWeather to false>><<set $readFlightPlan to false>><<set $readAircraft to false>><<set $readField to false>><<set $methodical to false>><<set $vmNote to false>><<set $vmReply to false>><<set $plugPulled to false>><<set $tested to false>><<set $testShowedDrop to false>><<set $delayed to false>><<set $heatSoak to false>><<set $missBegan to false>><<set $routing to "">><<set $stretched to false>><<set $isolated to false>><<set $singleMag to false>><<set $divert to "">><<set $pressOn to 0>><<set $grantSaw to false>><</link>>
</div>
