:: Ground_Overnight_Decide [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Announcing the overnight"])>>

You say it plainly, because that's how the good calls deserve to be said: the airplane stays until a mechanic who isn't guessing has had that magneto on a bench. Tonight is Alpine. You'll cover the rooms and the dinner and whatever the Monday costs.

Grant takes the legal pad off his knee and squares it on his lap, which you have learned is his tell for choosing among prepared remarks.

<div class="pax-quote">"Last argument, then I rest. The evidence hasn't changed since the run-up: the numbers passed, the procedure worked, the book is satisfied. What changed is that we talked about it longer. If a client reversed a sound position because the negotiation ran late, you'd call that fatigue, not judgment. Persuade me there's a difference and I'll carry your bags to the motel myself."</div>

It is, as usual, a good argument. The engine ticks as it cools, within limits and unexplained.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You hold the call, and give him the honest answer: you can't out-argue him, and you don't have to. The seat you're renting him doesn't come with a vote on this one." "Overnight_Logistics">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Held the overnight; invoked the seat, kindly"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. You hold the call and offer him the machinery of your logistics: your phone, the rental outfit's number, the motel, the 6 a.m. option, whatever solves his Monday." "Overnight_Logistics">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Held the overnight; solved his Monday with him"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "C. He wants the car, you can hear it. You help him hunt down the rental outfit tonight and send him east on four wheels while you stay with the airplane." "End_Deadline_Drive">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Sent Grant east by car tonight"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "D. The argument lands. The engine is cool now, the evening is kind, and a clean recheck would be a third data point. You reverse yourself and go." "Launch_Cooled">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Reversed the overnight and launched"])>>
  <<set $delayed to true>>
  <<set $badchoices to $badchoices + 1>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Overnight_Logistics [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Making the overnight work"])>>

He nods once, the way he probably nods at judges, and gets to work beside you instead of against you. The rental outfit's phone rings into the Sunday void. The motel answers on the second ring and has two rooms; the clerk gives walking directions that consist of the word "downhill."

The Monday problem gets solved the way real ones do: Grant calls opposing counsel from the shade of the wing, absorbs thirty seconds of theatrical inconvenience, and moves the deposition to one o'clock. "Depositions move," he says, pocketing the phone. "I try to save my outrage for things that don't."

You call Leah. She listens to the whole shape of it and says the thing she always says, which is the reason you married into this family twice over: "Good. Come home when it's boring."

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Dinner in town, the airplane chained under the biggest sky in Texas." "Overnight_Evening">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["To town for the evening"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Overnight_Evening [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Alpine evening; morning plan set"])>>

The diner is good in the way small-town diners are good: nothing on the menu is a metaphor. Grant preps his witness outline at the corner table for an hour, then puts it away and asks real questions about flying, the kind he'd never ask while an argument was live. Why the book number exists. What a magneto actually does. Why "within limits" and "airworthy" aren't the same word. You answer, and somewhere in there the day's ledger quietly balances.

Walking back, the sky does its high-desert thing: too many stars to look casual about.

Morning plan: coffee at seven, out to the field, a cold-engine recheck with the town's mechanics awake and reachable, and a decision made in daylight with all options open.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. Morning comes. You go run it up." "Morning_Run">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Monday morning recheck"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: Morning_Run [scenario]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Monday: cold engine, clean numbers, open shop"])>>

Monday, 7:40 a.m., the field already busy by Alpine standards: one Cessna in the pattern and the maintenance hangar's doors rolled open, a shop fan running inside. The desert morning is fifty-nine degrees and the airplane starts like it slept well.

The run-up, cold: left 70, right 85, split of 15, smooth as glass both ways. A cold engine in cold air, telling you about this minute. By now you could write the footnote yourself.

The difference between last night and this morning isn't the numbers. It's the open hangar doors two hundred yards away, and Grant's deposition sitting safely at one o'clock.

<div class="choice-list">
<<link "A. You taxi it to the open shop first and put the mag on the bench before you bet anything else on it." "End_Overnight_Shop">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Shop first, flight after"])>>
<</link>>

<<link "B. Clean and cold, you fly it home now and book it with your own mechanic for this week; Grant makes his one o'clock with hours to spare." "End_Overnight_Clean">>
  <<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Flew home Monday; scope booked at home"])>>
<</link>>
</div>

<p class="main-menu-wrap"><a href="/" class="main-menu-btn">Main Menu</a></p>

:: End_Home_Arrived [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: home at San Marcos"])>>

The tires chirp on 26 and San Marcos ground taxis you home through the last of the color in the sky. Leah's headlights are waiting at the hangar row; Grant is out of the airplane before the prop stops turning, kissing his sister's cheek, already narrating. "Your husband," you hear him say, "runs a tougher courtroom than mine."

Thursday, because you booked it Monday morning<<if $vmReply>>, and because a west Texas mechanic's text kept reading itself to you at red lights<</if>>, your own shop pulls the right magneto. The distributor block comes out with a carbon track across it like a pencil line: a carbon path where spark had been finding its own way home, worse when hot, invisible on a bench that isn't looking for it. "Ran fine for you, did it?" your mechanic says, holding it up. "It was going to get louder every hot start until it got loud somewhere you'd remember."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>You saw a 240 RPM drop with real roughness, ran the correct clearing procedure, and got numbers inside the book. <<if $tested>>Then you spent ten minutes and a few gallons buying evidence: a full-power test profile overhead the field, which the fault happened not to attend.<<elseif $delayed>>Then you took the one mitigation the afternoon offered for free: time. A cooler engine, cooler air, softer light, and a recheck before launch.<<else>>Then you flew home.<</if>> The flight was uneventful. The magneto was failing the entire time.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>The pressure in this scenario never raised its voice. It cross-examined. Grant's argument was locally sound: the limits were met, the procedure behaved as designed, the base rate favored fouling. What his argument could not supply, because no argument can, is the distinction between <em>within limits</em> and <em>understood</em>. The drop that clears is consistent with two stories, and only one of them is finished with you. <<if $badchoices gte 1>>Reversing a made decision under sustained persuasion is worth an honest look in the mirror: the evidence didn't change between your no and your yes. Only the argument did.<</if>></p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p><<if $tested>>The test profile is the counterintuitive move that looks aggressive and is actually conservative: it converts an argument into an observation, with a runway attached the whole time. It didn't catch this fault, because intermittents keep their own calendar. That doesn't make it wasted. It makes it evidence with error bars.<<else>>When a discrepancy clears without a proven cause, the honest options all involve buying information: a test profile overhead the field, a cool-down that removes the fault's favorite condition, a bench, or a night. You bought some. The outcome cooperated.<</if>> The debrief question that matters is the one outcome bias hides: would this decision look as good if the carbon track had spoken up over the Glass Mountains? Judge the bet, not the payout. 14 CFR 91.7 makes the pilot the airworthiness authority of record for exactly this gray zone. The book number is where that authority starts, not where it ends.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A cleared discrepancy without a confirmed cause is a loan, not a verdict. You can't out-argue a good lawyer, and you don't have to: the seat decides, and the seat's job is to be right about the airplane, not about the debate.</p>
</div>
<div class="restart">
