:: End_Reposition_KFST [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: repositioned to the shop's doorstep"])>>

The motel's air conditioner has two settings, arctic and off, and the interstate hums all night like a distant frequency. Monday at 8:05 the shop's phone rings you before you can ring it: they found the note. By 10:30 the right mag is on the bench and the mechanic is holding the distributor block up to the window light, whistling at the carbon track scorched across it. "Hot-start special," he says on the phone. "You want the old block for your desk? Some guys do." Grant, who took the shop's loaner car east at dawn, makes his continuance-free Monday by twenty minutes.

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>The fault confessed overhead the field, and you spent the confession carefully: fifty-one gentle miles to the doorstep of the region's open-Monday shop, in deep daylight, at reduced power, with an interstate under the wing and altitude in hand. The airplane was on a bench eighteen hours later and home two days after that.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>This is a genuinely debatable call, and the debrief should say so out loud. Against it: you launched an airplane with a known, demonstrated, intermittent ignition fault, and intermittents do not owe you a repeat of their mild opening act. For it: every mitigation that exists was actually applied: power reduced below the fault's favorite regime, routing over a road and a runway, altitude banked, daylight deep, the destination chosen precisely because the bench was there. What separates this from the press-on paths is not luck. The exposure was designed, bounded, and pointed at the fix.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>If you fly a known-degraded airplane at all, fly it the way this leg was flown: shortest useful distance, kindest power, maximum outs, and a reason on the other end that actually retires the risk (a bench, not a barbecue). The equally correct answer was the tie-down at Alpine and a Tuesday mechanic; that version costs a day and buys certainty. Reasonable pilots split here. What they don't get to split on is doing it at night, over the empty, or at full power: those versions are a different scenario, and it appears elsewhere in this one.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>A ferry flight to the fix is a designed exposure, not a continuation of the mission. Design it or decline it.</p>
</div>
