:: End_Overnight_Clean [scenario ending]
<<set $pathArray to $pathArray.concat(["Ending: Monday flight home, scope booked"])>>

The Monday flight home is one hour and forty-eight minutes of anticlimax, which you have learned to count as winnings. Cool morning, smooth engine, the Hill Country green-gold out the right window. Grant naps like a man acquitted. He makes his one o'clock with a margin wide enough to bill somebody for, and his text that evening reads: "Deposition went long. Nobody died of continuance. Noted for future reference."

Thursday your own shop pulls the right mag. Carbon track across the distributor block, scorched and unambiguous. Your mechanic photographs it next to a fresh one and sends both pictures with a one-line caption: "Cold, it behaves. Hot, it freelances. Good call not trusting it Sunday."

<hr>
<div class="debrief">
<h3>What happened</h3>
<p>You held an unpopular no on Sunday, converted it into logistics instead of an argument, and flew home Monday on a cold engine and a clean check, with the bench already booked. The bench then told you what the Sunday engine had been trying to say: the fault was real, heat-activated, and patient.</p>
<h3>ADM analysis</h3>
<p>Notice what the Monday-morning clean numbers almost did: they made Sunday's decision look excessive. That's outcome bias running in reverse, and pilots who overnight on a discrepancy meet it in the morning every time: the airplane behaves, the sunk cost aches, and the temptation is to quietly downgrade yesterday's judgment. The bench's photograph is the antidote worth remembering: the decision was right when you made it, with the information you had, and it stayed right after the evidence arrived. It would have stayed right even if the block had come back clean, because reasonable doubt about ignition over that country was worth one motel night at any exchange rate.</p>
<h3>What good judgment looks like here</h3>
<p>The full sequence, which is rarer than any single piece. A no-go held without drama. The passenger's problem treated as real and solved with him rather than dismissed. The flight resumed under conditions that took away the fault's favorite weather (cold engine, cold morning, help awake along the route). And the discrepancy retired on a bench instead of by fading memory. The old joke about useless things (runway behind you, altitude above you) earns a third clause here: a mechanic you didn't call.</p>
<h3>Key takeaway</h3>
<p>Right decisions sometimes feel wrong the next morning. Book the bench anyway; the block doesn't lie.</p>
</div>
